<DocsLayout title="Project 7: The Managed Database" description="Build a patient appointment booking system with RDS PostgreSQL, Alembic migrations, ALB, blue/green deployment, and Grafana monitoring.">
  <h1 class="mb-2">Project 7: The Managed Database</h1>
  <p class="text-xl text-primary font-medium mb-6">"I can set up and operate a managed database with migrations, backups, and point-in-time recovery."</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll build</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">A patient appointment booking and clinical notes system for Coastal Physio — Dr. Megan Chen's physiotherapy practice with three locations across the Mornington Peninsula (Mornington, Rosebud, Dromana). Patient registration, appointment scheduling across three locations, practitioner assignment, and clinical notes. Three user types: patients, practitioners, and admin/reception. Data is sensitive — medical records under the Australian Privacy Act.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What's new (the +1)</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Managed database. Until now, your database was a container you ran yourself — you were responsible for backups, updates, and recovery. This project moves the database to AWS RDS PostgreSQL: automated backups, automated patching, monitoring, and point-in-time recovery. You write Terraform to provision it, Alembic to manage migrations, and you practice recovering data.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Alongside RDS, you add an Application Load Balancer (ALB) in front of your EC2 instance, run blue/green deployments for zero-downtime releases, and set up Grafana dashboards for real observability. You also switch from GitHub Projects to Linear for project management — same kanban concepts, different tool.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Why this matters:</strong> Databases hold everything that matters. If the application crashes, you redeploy. If the database is lost, the business is lost. RDS handles the operational burden — automated backups, patching, failover — so you can focus on schema design and data integrity. Alembic makes schema changes safe and reversible. The ALB and blue/green deployment mean you can ship changes without taking the system offline.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What success looks like</h2>
  <Checklist items={[
    "RDS PostgreSQL is provisioned via Terraform with automated daily backups",
    "Every schema change goes through an Alembic migration — no manual database edits",
    "ALB routes traffic to EC2 with HTTPS termination via ACM certificate",
    "Blue/green deployment ships new versions with zero downtime",
    "Grafana dashboards show application metrics, RDS metrics, and system metrics",
    "Point-in-time recovery drill: restore the database to a specific timestamp and verify",
    "Megan can book appointments across all three locations and practitioners can write clinical notes",
  ]} />

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll learn</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Provision and configure RDS PostgreSQL with Terraform</li>
    <li>Manage database schema changes with Alembic migrations</li>
    <li>Set up an Application Load Balancer (ALB) with HTTPS via ACM</li>
    <li>Implement blue/green deployment for zero-downtime releases</li>
    <li>Build Grafana dashboards for application and infrastructure metrics</li>
    <li>Use Linear for project management (transferable kanban skills)</li>
    <li>Handle sensitive data with appropriate access controls and backup strategies</li>
    <li>Run a point-in-time recovery drill to prove data resilience</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Tech stack</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>React + FastAPI + RDS PostgreSQL</li>
    <li>EC2 behind ALB, Terraform for all infrastructure</li>
    <li>Alembic for database migrations</li>
    <li>Grafana (self-hosted on EC2 or Grafana Cloud free tier)</li>
    <li>Linear for project management</li>
    <li>GitHub Actions for CI/CD with blue/green deployment</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Completed <a href="/web-dev/projects/6">Project 6</a> and <a href="/web-dev/checkpoints/after-p6">Checkpoint After Project 6</a></li>
    <li>A <a href="https://linear.app">Linear</a> free account (you'll set this up during the project)</li>
    <li>A <a href="https://grafana.com">Grafana Cloud</a> free account (or plan to self-host on EC2)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Estimated time</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">2-3 weeks. The planning artifacts follow the established pattern. The new dimensions — RDS provisioning, Alembic migrations, ALB configuration, blue/green deployment, Grafana setup, and Linear onboarding — add significant infrastructure work beyond application development.</p>

